  "Aye, y're likely t' do a bit o' thot hereabouts," affirms Adaon.  "Nae 
much ye ken do to get around it.  >Fighting< is a way of life in the 
untamed wilderness.
  "If ye join the bards, ye'll find that ye are nae a toe-to-toe hackin' 
machine.  Our strength lies in versatility and subtle influence than 
direct confrontation.  Aye, we can wear quite a bit o' armor, and 
wield just about any weapon ye choose, even two at once, but we
don't train for rigorous combat.  That's what ye got fighters for.
  "No, bards are instead mediators.  Wi' our charm and intelligent wit, 
we can defuse quite a few brawls before they begin, and sometimes 
even after.  That be a valuable skill when ye travel wi' headstrong 
friends.  They get ye all int' trouble, and ye are there t' pull y'r fat 
out o' the fire."  Adaon chuckles.  "It's happened t' me a few times, 
meself.
  "There also be some war chants to rally the spirit o' y'r comrades, if 
ye be of a mind t' learn them.  Verra effective, too.  And we teach ye 
a bit about what t' do after battle, as well.  Aye, >fighting< is not just 
about swingin' a sword.  That's where other guilds fall short o' the 
bards.  The fighters can fight better, but that's all they do!  We 
>bards< have >talents< they only dream of mastering.
  "T' gi' ye a bit o' advice:  it dinnae matter which guild ye join, 
teamwork is the key t' returning alive from questing.  Bein' a bard 
just gives ye an edge, for by havin' some talent in everything, ye can 
judge the strengths and weaknesses o' y'r party, and thereby be a 
verra effective leader.  And if ye be in a small party or on y'r own, 
your variety of skills should give ye the resourcefulness to make it 
through."
